The Americas
------------
[5] Ecuador (Tungurahua)
Date: Mon 3 Oct 2011
Source: El universo [in Spanish, machine trans. edited]
http://www.eluniverso.com/2011/10/03/1/1364/brote-sarampion.htm


An outbreak of measles in the province of Tungurahua has alerted the
health authorities. Originally appearing in a rural community in the
parish of Quisapincha, it then spread to Ambato evading
epidemiological surveillance controls. The number of suspected cases
of the disease, which on Tue 27 Sep 2011 was 31, had risen to 48 by
Thu 29 Sep 2011, [and according to a more recent report of Tue 4 Oct
2011, the total is now 68. - Mod.CP].

According to the Health Director of the province, the indigenous
population is worst affected due to past reluctance to accept
vaccination A program of measles vaccination is now being implemented
throughout the province.

However, on account of the mobility of the population, especially on
weekdays, it will not be surprising if the disease spreads to other
sectors of the population. Consequently, we must endeavor to protect
children and people who have impaired immunity. It will be a priority
also to spread knowledge of the symptoms of the disease in order that
immediate treatment is sought.

--
